  <Name>k__BackingField: James (Jacob)
  fancyName: 
  nickname: jas
  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 69cda689d36a6b64ca4a020e1d829e9f, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Faith and Wisdom'
      title: Faith and Wisdom
      number: 1
      content: "Greetings! My name is Jacob, [[COMMENT(0)]] and I\u2019m a love-slave
        of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ. I\u2019m writing to all the twelve tribes
        of Israel who have been sown as seeds  among the nations."
      comments:
      - number: 1:1
        content: '  James is actually the Hebrew name Jacob, the name of the man
          who had twelve sons that formed the twelve tribes of Israel.      As translated
          from the Aramaic, which was the language spoken by Jesus and his disciples.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'My fellow believers, when it seems as though you are facing nothing
        but difficulties, see it as an invaluable opportunity to experience the greatest
        joy that you can! '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'For you know that when your faith is tested [[COMMENT(0)]] it stirs
        up in you the power of endurance. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  Or \u201Cwhen faith passes the test.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: And then as your endurance grows even stronger, it will release perfection
        into every part of your being until there is nothing missing and nothing
        lacking.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "And if anyone longs to be wise, ask God for wisdom and he will give
        it! He won\u2019t see your lack of wisdom as an opportunity to scold you
        over your failures but he will overwhelm your failures with his generous
        grace. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cwith an open hand.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Just make sure you ask empowered by confident faith without doubting
        that you will receive. For the ambivalent person believes one minute and
        doubts the next. Being undecided makes you become like the rough seas driven
        and tossed by the wind. You\u2019re up one minute and tossed down the next. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7-8: '
      title: 
      number: 7-8
      content: "When you are half-hearted and wavering it leaves you unstable. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Can you really expect to receive anything from the Lord when you\u2019re
        in that condition?"
      comments:
      - number: "1:7\u20138"
        content: "  Or \u201Crestless\u201D or \u201Cdisengaged.\u201D    "
    - name: '7-8: '
      title: 
      number: 7-8
      content: "When you are half-hearted and wavering it leaves you unstable. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        Can you really expect to receive anything from the Lord when you\u2019re
        in that condition?"
      comments:
      - number: "1:7\u20138"
        content: "  Or \u201Crestless\u201D or \u201Cdisengaged.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'The believer who is poor still has reasons to boast, for he has been
        placed on high. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'But those who are rich should boast in how God has brought them low
        and humbled them, for all their earthly glory will one day fade away like
        a wildflower in the meadow. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: For as the scorching heat of the sun causes the petals of the wildflower
        to fall off and lose its appearance of beauty, [[COMMENT(0)]] so the rich
        in the midst of their pursuit of wealth will wither away.
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: '  In the land of the Bible there were many deserts with arid land.
          The rainy season is quite short and the burning heat of the sun scorched
          the earth until the next season of rain arrived. We live in a constantly
          changing world with riches and beauty quickly fading. Our hope is set on
          things above.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "If your faith remains strong, even while surrounded by life\u2019s
        difficulties, you will continue to experience the untold blessings of God!
        True happiness comes as you pass the test with faith, and receive the victorious
        crown of life promised to every lover of God!"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "When you are tempted don\u2019t ever say, \u201CGod is tempting me,\u201D
        for God is incapable of being tempted by evil and he is never the source
        of temptation. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Instead it is each person\u2019s own desires and thoughts that drag
        them into evil and lure [[COMMENT(0)]] them away into darkness. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:14
        content: "  Or \u201Chooked by the bait of evil from their own desires.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Evil desires give birth to evil actions. And when sin is fully mature
        it can murder you! '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So my friends, don\u2019t be fooled by your own desires!"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Every gift [[COMMENT(0)]] God freely gives us is good and perfect, 
        streaming down from the Father of lights,  who shines from the heavens with
        no hidden shadow or darkness  and is never subject to change. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:17
        content: "  Or \u201Clegacy.\u201D      The Aramaic word used here,  , means
          \u201Ccomplete, wholesome, abundant, sufficient, enough, and perfect.\u201D     
          Jesus calls us the light of the world () and Paul describes believers as
          \u201Cshining lights\u201D () in this world. God is our Father, he created
          angels but he brought us into new birth. The Greek word    (\u201Cfrom
          above\u201D) is used by Jesus in describing to Nicodemus that we are born
          from above. We are lights born from above. See also  .      Or \u201Cshadow
          of turning.\u201D The implication is there is nothing that you will find
          wrong with God, nothing in him that could even remotely appear to be evil
          hiding. The more you get to know him the more you realize how beautiful
          and holy he is.    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'God was delighted [[COMMENT(0)]] to give us birth by the truth of
        his infallible Word  so that we would fulfill his chosen destiny for us and
        become the favorite ones out of all his creation! '
      comments:
      - number: 1:18
        content: "  Or \u201CGod having decided gave us birth.\u201D The comparison
          in this passage is striking. Sin gives birth to death, God from his pure
          desires gives us birth to bring him glory.      The Aramaic can be translated
          \u201Cthe word of the rainbow-sign.\u201D That is, the unbreakable new
          covenant promises we have as new creatures in Christ.      Or \u201Ca kind
          of firstfruits of his creations\u201D or \u201Cthe pledge [down-payment]
          of a still further creation [a more complete harvest].\u201D    "
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'My dearest brothers and sisters, take this to heart: Be quick to
        listen, [[COMMENT(0)]] but slow to speak. And be slow to become angry, '
      comments:
      - number: 1:19
        content: "  Although the Greek does not supply an object we are to listen
          to, it is obvious in the context that we should listen to one another,
          to God\u2019s voice, and to his Word. May God give us listening hearts.    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "for human anger is never a legitimate tool to promote God\u2019s
        righteous purpose. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:20
        content: "  Or \u201CGod\u2019s righteousness will never attach itself to
          human anger.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "So this is why we abandon everything morally impure [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and all forms of wicked conduct.  Instead, with a sensitive spirit  we absorb
        God\u2019s Word, which has been implanted within our nature, for the Word
        of Life has power to continually deliver us. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:21
        content: "  The Aramaic word used here can mean \u201Cdemonic activities.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cexcesses of evil.\u201D      Due to the Greek sentence construction,
          this clause may refer to what preceded it, \u201Cabandon&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.
          all forms of wicked conduct with a gentle [meek] heart.\u201D      Or \u201Csave
          our souls.\u201D The Greek uses the effective aorist active infinitive   
          () from    () and could refer to the ultimate salvation of our souls (personality,
          emotions, thoughts) and/or our eternal salvation.    "
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Don\u2019t just listen to the Word of Truth and not respond to it,
        for that is the essence of self-deception. So always let his Word become
        like poetry written and fulfilled by your life! [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:22
        content: "  Or \u201Cbe a poet [doer] of the Word.\u201D    "
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "If you listen to the Word and don\u2019t live out the message you
        hear, you become like the person who looks in the mirror of the Word to discover
        the reflection of his face in the beginning. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:23
        content: "  Or \u201Crealizing his beginning [genesis] face\u201D or \u201Cstudying
          the face he was born with.\u201D    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'You perceive how God sees you in the mirror of the Word, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        but then you go out and forget  your divine origin. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:24
        content: "  For the believer, seeing the man \u201Cin the mirror\u201D is
          seeing how God sees us from the beginning, even before the fall of Adam
          which resulted in sin\u2019s devastation to human hearts. The man in the
          mirror is the new creation man.      The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cdrift
          away from.\u201D    "
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "But those who set their gaze deeply into the perfecting law of liberty
        [[COMMENT(0)]] are fascinated by and respond to the truth they hear and are
        strengthened by it\u2014they experience God\u2019s blessing in all that they
        do! "
      comments:
      - number: 1:25
        content: "  This is referred to as the \u201Croyal law of love\u201D in   
          and the \u201Claw of liberty\u201D in  .      See  .    "
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: If someone believes they have a relationship with God but fails to
        guard his words then his heart is drifting away and his religion is shallow
        and empty. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:26
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CIf one presumes
          to be religious but doesn\u2019t guard his tongue, he deceives himself
          and his religion is useless.\u201D    "
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "True spirituality [[COMMENT(0)]] that is pure in the eyes of our
        Father God is to make a difference in the lives of the orphans,  and widows
        in their troubles, and to refuse to be corrupted by the world\u2019s values."
      comments:
      - number: 1:27
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CTrue ministry.\u201D     
          The Greek word    means \u201Cthe fatherless\u201D or \u201Cthe comfortless.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Royal Law of Love Excludes Prejudice'
      title: The Royal Law of Love Excludes Prejudice
      number: 1
      content: "My dear brothers and sisters, fellow believers in our glorious Lord
        Jesus Christ\u2014how could we say that we have faith in him and yet we favor
        one group of people above another? [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CDon\u2019t be taken in by
          the face mask of people, but hold to the faith in the glory of our Lord
          Jesus the Messiah.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Suppose an influential man comes into your worship meeting wearing
        gold rings and expensive clothing, and also a homeless man in shabby clothes
        comes in. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "If you show special attention to the rich man in expensive clothes
        and say, \u201CHere\u2019s a seat of honor for you right up front!\u201D
        but you turn and say to the poor beggar dressed in rags, \u201CYou can stand
        over here,\u201D or \u201CSit over there on the floor in the back,\u201D
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201CSit on the floor before our
          footstool.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "then you\u2019ve demonstrated gross prejudice among yourselves and
        used evil standards of judgment!"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So listen carefully, my dear brothers and sisters, hasn\u2019t God
        chosen [[COMMENT(0)]] the poor in the world\u2019s eyes to be those who are
        rich in faith?  And won\u2019t they be the heirs of the kingdom-realm he
        promised to those who love him? "
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: "  The Greek word for \u201Cchosen\u201D is  , which is a form of   
          (speak).      See  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But yet you insult and shun the poor in your efforts to impress the
        rich! [[COMMENT(0)]] Isn\u2019t it the wealthy who exploit you and drag you
        into court? "
      comments:
      - number: 2:6
        content: '  See also  .    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Aren\u2019t they the very ones who blaspheme the beautiful name of
        the One you now belong to? [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:7
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe worthy name which was invoked over you (at your
          baptism).\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Your calling is to fulfill the royal law of love [[COMMENT(0)]] as
        given to us in this Scripture: \u201CYou must love and value your neighbor
        as you love and value yourself!\u201D For keeping this law is the noble way
        to live. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:8
        content: '  It is a royal law because it is given by our King, but since
          he has made us kings and priests, it becomes the royal law of love given
          to his royal sons and daughters who are heirs with him.      See  ;  ; 
          ;  ;  ;  ;  .    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: But when you show prejudice you commit sin and you violate this royal
        law of love!
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'For the one who attempts to keep all of the law of Moses but fails
        in just one point has become guilty of breaking the law in every respect! '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "For the same One who tells us, \u201CDo not commit adultery,\u201D
        also said, \u201CDo not murder.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] Now if you don\u2019t
        commit adultery but do commit murder, you are still guilty as a law-breaker. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: '  See  .    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So we must both speak and act in every respect like those who are
        destined to be tried by the perfect law of liberty, '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: Faith Works'
      title: Faith Works
      number: 13
      content: and remember that judgment is merciless for the one who judges others
        without mercy. So by showing mercy, you take dominion over judgment! [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 2:13
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CMercy triumphs
          over judgment.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'My dear brothers and sisters, what good is it if someone claims to
        have faith but demonstrates no good works to prove it? How could this kind
        of faith save anyone? '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'For example, if a brother or sister in the faith is poorly clothed
        and hungry '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "and you leave them saying, \u201CGood-bye. I hope you stay warm and
        have plenty to eat,\u201D but you don\u2019t provide them with a coat or
        even a cup of soup, what good is your faith? "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So then faith that doesn\u2019t involve action is phony. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:17
        content: "  Or \u201Cdead (fruitless).\u201D See also v.  .    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But someone might object and say, \u201COne person has faith and
        another person has works.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]] Go ahead then and prove to
        me that you have faith without works and I will show you faith by my works
        as proof that I believe. "
      comments:
      - number: 2:18
        content: '  Many scholars conclude that the ambiguity of the Greek text makes
          this the most difficult verse in all of James and perhaps in all of the
          New Testament to translate.    '
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "You can believe all you want that there is one true God, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        that\u2019s wonderful! But even the demons know this and tremble with fear
        before him,  yet they\u2019re unchanged\u2014they remain demons."
      comments:
      - number: 2:19
        content: "  Or \u201Cthat God is one,\u201D which is the Jewish    (see 
          ).      The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cthey writhe on their bellies
          in the dirt!\u201D    "
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'O&nbsp;feeble sons of Adam, [[COMMENT(0)]] do you need further evidence
        that faith divorced from good works is phony? '
      comments:
      - number: 2:20
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CO&nbsp;empty
          man.\u201D    "
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Wasn\u2019t our ancestor Abraham found righteous before God because
        of his works when he offered his son Isaac on the altar? "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Can\u2019t you see how his action cooperated with his faith and by
        his action faith found its full expression? "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "So in this way the Scripture was fulfilled:Because Abraham believed
        God, his faith was exchanged for God\u2019s righteousness. [[COMMENT(0)]]So
        he became known as the lover of God!   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:23
        content: "  Or \u201CAbraham\u2019s faith was credited to his account for
          righteousness.\u201D See  .      Or \u201Cthe one whom God loved,\u201D
          as translated from the Aramaic. Although the Greek text is most often translated
          \u201Cfriend of God,\u201D the Greek word    can also be used as the love
          that bonds friends together. See also  ;  ;    (LXX).    "
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "So now it\u2019s clear that a person is seen as righteous in God\u2019s
        eyes not merely by faith alone, but by his works."
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "And the same is true of the prostitute named Rahab who was found
        righteous in God\u2019s eyes by her works, for she received the spies into
        her home and helped them escape from the city by another route. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 2:25
        content: '  See  .  '
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: For just as a human body without the spirit is a dead corpse, so faith
        without the expression of good works is dead!
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Power of Your Words'
      title: The Power of Your Words
      number: 1
      content: "My dear brothers and sisters, don\u2019t be so eager to become a
        teacher in the church since you know that we who teach are held to a higher
        standard of judgment. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "We all fail in many areas, but especially with our words. Yet if
        we\u2019re able to bridle the words we say we are powerful enough to control
        ourselves in every way, and that means our character is mature and fully
        developed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Horses have bits and bridles in their mouths so that we can control
        and guide their large body. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: And the same with mighty ships, though they are massive and driven
        by fierce winds, yet they are steered by a tiny rudder at the direction of
        the person at the helm.
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'And so the tongue is a small part of the body yet it carries great
        power! [[COMMENT(0)]] Just think of how a small flame can set a huge forest
        ablaze. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cboasts of great things.\u201D The Aramaic can be translated
          \u201Cthe tongue has dominion.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'And the tongue is a fire! It can be compared to the sum total of
        wickedness [[COMMENT(0)]] and is the most dangerous part of our human body.
        It corrupts the entire body  and is a hellish flame!  It releases a fire
        that can burn throughout the course of human existence. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:6
        content: "  As translated from the Latin Vulgate. The Greek is \u201Ca world
          of wrongdoing.\u201D      It is possible that the body Jacob refers to
          here is the body of believers (a local church).      Or \u201Cis set ablaze
          by gehenna [hell].\u201D The Aramaic does not mention    but is simply
          \u201Cburns with fire.\u201D Gehenna is taken from the concept of \u201CThe
          Valley of Hinnom\u201D where rubbish was burned outside the city of Jerusalem,
          becoming a Hebrew metaphor for the fires of hell.      The Aramaic can
          be translated \u201Ca fire that passes through successive generations,
          rolling on like wheels.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'For every wild animal on earth including birds, creeping reptiles,
        and creatures of the sea and land [[COMMENT(0)]] have all been overpowered
        and tamed by humans, '
      comments:
      - number: 3:7
        content: '  Implied in the Greek and made explicit in the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "but the tongue is not able to be tamed. It\u2019s a fickle, unrestrained
        evil that spews out words full of toxic poison! "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'We use our tongue to praise God our Father [[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>).</smallcaps>
        and then turn around and curse a person who was made in his very image!   '
      comments:
      - number: 3:9
        content: "  Some Greek manuscripts have \u201CLord and Father.\u201D The
          Aramaic can be translated \u201CLord God\u201D (, the Aramaic equivalent
          to        The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cwe curse a person and pretend
          to be God!\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: Out of the same mouth we pour out words of praise one minute and curses
        the next. My brothers and sisters, this should never be!
      comments: []
    - name: '11-12: Wisdom from Above'
      title: Wisdom from Above
      number: 11-12
      content: Would you look for olives hanging on a fig tree or go to pick figs
        from a grapevine? Is it possible that fresh and bitter water can flow out
        of the same spring? So neither can a bitter spring produce fresh water. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: "3:11\u201312"
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '11-12: Wisdom from Above'
      title: Wisdom from Above
      number: 11-12
      content: Would you look for olives hanging on a fig tree or go to pick figs
        from a grapevine? Is it possible that fresh and bitter water can flow out
        of the same spring? So neither can a bitter spring produce fresh water. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: "3:11\u201312"
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "If you consider yourself to be wise and one who understands the ways
        of God, advertise it with a beautiful, fruitful [[COMMENT(0)]] life guided
        by wisdom\u2019s gentleness. Never brag or boast about what you\u2019ve done
        and you\u2019ll prove that you\u2019re truly wise. "
      comments:
      - number: 3:13
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "But if there is bitter jealousy or competition hiding in your heart,
        then don\u2019t deny it and try to compensate for it by boasting and being
        phony. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "For that has nothing to do with God\u2019s heavenly wisdom but can
        best be described as the wisdom of this world, both selfish [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and devilish.   "
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cunspiritual.\u201D      Or \u201Cbehaves like a demon.\u201D    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: So wherever jealousy [[COMMENT(0)]] and selfishness are uncovered,
        you will also find many troubles  and every kind of meanness.
      comments:
      - number: 3:16
        content: "  The Greek word for jealousy implies an obsession to promote one\u2019s
          self at the expense of others.      The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cchaos.\u201D
          The Greek can be translated \u201Cinstability\u201D or \u201Cdisorder.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'But the wisdom from above is always pure, [[COMMENT(0)]] filled with
        peace, considerate and teachable.  It is filled with love  and never displays
        prejudice or hypocrisy  in any form '
      comments:
      - number: 3:17
        content: "  Or \u201Choly.\u201D      A beautiful concept that means \u201Ceasy
          to correct\u201D or \u201Cready to be convinced\u201D or \u201Cwilling
          to yield to others.\u201D Is this true of your life?      As translated
          from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201Cmercy.\u201D      Or \u201Cnever wears
          a mask.\u201D  "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "and it always bears the beautiful harvest of righteousness! Good
        seeds of wisdom\u2019s fruit will be planted with peaceful acts by those
        who cherish making peace."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Living Close to God'
      title: Living Close to God
      number: 1
      content: "What is the cause of your conflicts and quarrels with each other?
        Doesn\u2019t the battle begin inside of you as you fight to have your own
        way and fulfill your own desires? "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "You jealously want what others have so you begin to see yourself
        as better than others. You scheme with envy and harm [[COMMENT(0)]] others
        to selfishly obtain what you crave\u2014that\u2019s why you quarrel and fight.
        And all the time you don\u2019t obtain what you want because you won\u2019t
        ask God for it! "
      comments:
      - number: 4:2
        content: "  Or \u201Ckill,\u201D however, the Greek words for \u201Ckill\u201D
          and \u201Cenvy\u201D are almost the same.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "And if you ask, you won\u2019t receive it for you\u2019re asking
        with corrupt motives, [[COMMENT(0)]] seeking only to fulfill your own selfish
        desires. "
      comments:
      - number: 4:3
        content: "  The Greek word for corrupt motives is    and can be translated
          \u201Csick,\u201D or \u201Csickly.\u201D James is exhorting us not to pray
          \u201Csickly prayers.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "You have become spiritual adulterers who are having an affair, an
        unholy relationship with the world. Don\u2019t you know that flirting with
        the world\u2019s values places you at odds with God? Whoever chooses to be
        the world\u2019s friend makes himself God\u2019s enemy!"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Does the Scripture mean nothing to you that says, \u201CThe Spirit
        that God breathed into our hearts is a jealous Lover who intensely desires
        to have more and more of us\u201D? [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:5
        content: '  Although it is difficult to find a verse from the Old Testament
          that reads exactly how Jacob quotes it, the possibility remains that it
          becomes a general statement of what the Bible teaches, or even a quotation
          from an older translation not available today. We must always realize that
          the Holy Spirit pursues us relentlessly and takes it very personally when
          we turn from him to pursue friendship with the world.    '
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But he continues to pour out more and more grace [[COMMENT(0)]] upon
        us. For it says,\u201CGod resists you when you are proudbut continually pours
        out grace when you are humble.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: 4:6
        content: "  Or \u201Che gives us a greater gift\u201D or \u201Cthe grace
          [favor] he gives us is stronger.\u201D      See  .    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'So then, surrender to God. Stand up to the devil and resist him and
        he will flee in agony. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 4:7
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic. The accuser will flee in agony
          because of the One who stands with you.    '
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Move your heart closer and closer to God, and he will come even closer
        to you. [[COMMENT(0)]] But make sure you cleanse your life, you sinners,
        and keep your heart pure and stop doubting.   '
      comments:
      - number: 4:8
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cand he will be touching you.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cyou double-minded.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Feel the pain of your sin, be sorrowful and weep! Let your joking
        around [[COMMENT(0)]] be turned into mourning and your joy into deep humiliation. '
      comments:
      - number: 4:9
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.    '
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: Be willing to be made low before the Lord and he will exalt you!
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Dear friends, as part of God\u2019s family, never speak against another
        family member, for when you slander a brother or sister you violate [[COMMENT(0)]]
        God\u2019s law of love. And your duty is not to make yourself a judge of
        the law of love   by saying that it doesn\u2019t apply to you,   but your
        duty is to obey it!   "
      comments:
      - number: 4:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cspeak against.\u201D      See also  ;  .      Or \u201Cto
          be a judge of the law.\u201D      Implied in the argument Jacob makes to
          refrain from being a judge of the law.  "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "There is only one true Lawgiver and Judge, the One who has the power
        to save and destroy\u2014so who do you think you are to judge your neighbor?"
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Listen, those of you who are boasting, \u201CToday or tomorrow we\u2019ll
        go to another city and spend some time and go into business and make heaps
        of profit!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "But you don\u2019t have a clue what tomorrow may bring. For your
        fleeting life is but a warm breath of air that is visible in the cold only
        for a moment and then vanishes! "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Instead you should say, \u201COur tomorrows are in the Lord\u2019s
        hands and if he is willing we will live life to its fullest and do this or
        that.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But here you are, boasting in your ignorance, for to be presumptuous
        about what you\u2019ll do tomorrow is evil!"
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "So if you know of an opportunity to do the right thing today, yet
        you refrain from doing it, you\u2019re guilty of sin."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Warning to the Rich'
      title: Warning to the Rich
      number: 1
      content: "Listen all you who are rich, for it\u2019s time to weep and howl
        over the misery [[COMMENT(0)]] that will overtake you! "
      comments:
      - number: 5:1
        content: '  The Aramaic word can refer to demonic torment.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Your riches lie rotting, your fine clothing eaten by moths, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'and your gold and silver are corroded as a witness against you. You
        have hoarded up treasure for the last days but it will become a fire to burn
        your flesh. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Listen! Can\u2019t you hear the cries of the laborers [[COMMENT(0)]]
        over the wages you fraudulently held back from those who worked for you? 
        The cries for justice of those you\u2019ve cheated have reached the ears
        of the Lord of armies! "
      comments:
      - number: 5:4
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe reapers\u201D (of your fields).      Or \u201Cthose
          who worked in your fields.\u201D      Or \u201CLord Sabaoth.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "You have indulged yourselves with every luxury and pleasure this
        world offers, but you\u2019re only stuffing your heart full for a day of
        slaughter. "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'You have condemned and murdered good and innocent people [[COMMENT(0)]]
        who had no power to defend themselves. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe righteous one,\u201D a possible reference to the
          death of Jesus.      Or \u201Cwill not (God) resist you?\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Meanwhile, brothers and sisters, we must be patient and filled with
        expectation as we wait for the appearing [[COMMENT(0)]] of the Lord. Think
        about the farmer who has to patiently wait for the earth\u2019s harvest as
        it ripens because of the early and latter rains. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:7
        content: "  This is the abstract Greek word    which can mean \u201Carrival,
          presence, becoming manifest, appearing.\u201D    is taken from the present
          participle    a compound word of    (beside) and    (to be seen, made visible).
          It has little to do with distance or space, but with becoming visible,
          such as an uncovering or revealing what is nearby. It is commonly used
          for the return of our Lord Jesus Christ.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So you also, keep your hopes high and be patient, for the presence
        of the Lord is drawing closer. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 5:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cnear at hand.\u201D The Greek word    is taken from
          the word  , which means to take by the hand, to throttle, or to hold the
          reins. (See  , Gr. 1448 and 1451.)    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "Since each of you are part of God\u2019s family never complain or
        grumble about each other [[COMMENT(0)]] so that judgment will not come on
        you, for the true Judge is near and very ready to appear! "
      comments:
      - number: 5:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cdon\u2019t blame others\u201D (for your troubles).     
          Or \u201Cat the gate.\u201D    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'My brothers and sisters, take [[COMMENT(0)]] the prophets as your
        mentors. They have prophesied in the name of the Lord  and it brought them
        great sufferings, yet they patiently endured. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:10
        content: "  Or \u201Creceive.\u201D      That is, by the Lord\u2019s authority.
          See also v.  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'We honor them as our heroes [[COMMENT(0)]] because they remained
        faithful even while enduring great sufferings. And you have heard of all
        that Job went through and we can now see that the Lord ultimately treated
        him with wonderful kindness, revealing how tenderhearted he really is! '
      comments:
      - number: 5:11
        content: "  Or \u201Cwe regard them as blessed.\u201D      See  ;  .    "
    - name: '12: Prayer for the Sick'
      title: Prayer for the Sick
      number: 12
      content: "Above all we must be those who never need to verify our speech as
        truthful by swearing by the heavens or the earth or any other oath. [[COMMENT(0)]]
        But instead we must be so full of integrity that our \u201CYes\u201D or \u201CNo\u201D
        is convincing enough and we do not stumble into hypocrisy. "
      comments:
      - number: 5:12
        content: "  See  .      Some Greek manuscripts read \u201Cstumble into hypocrisy,\u201D
          while others have, \u201Cstumble into judgment.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Are there any believers in your fellowship suffering great hardship
        and distress? Encourage them to pray! [[COMMENT(0)]] Are there happy, cheerful
        ones among you? Encourage them to sing out their praises!   '
      comments:
      - number: 5:13
        content: "  See  ;  .      Or \u201Cpluck the strings of a harp\u201D or
          \u201Csing a psalm.\u201D    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Are there any sick among you? Then ask the elders of the church to
        come and pray over the sick and anoint them with oil in the name of our Lord. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'And the prayer of faith [[COMMENT(0)]] will heal the sick  and the
        Lord will raise them up,  and if they have committed sins  they will be forgiven. '
      comments:
      - number: 5:15
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe claim of faith.\u201D      This is not the Greek
          usually used for sickness or disease. The word    can also mean \u201Cthose
          who are weary and worn down,\u201D and in the context could possibly refer
          to believers who have been arguing with each other, leaving them spiritually
          weak.      That is, restore them to health. This could be a subtle hint
          of a resurrection.      Or \u201Cdoer of sin.\u201D There is a clear implication
          in this passage that the sickness (weakness) referred to is the result
          of sin. See also  .      This may be speaking of the church elders who
          are forgiving the arguing believers and restoring them back into fellowship.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: Confess and acknowledge how you have offended one another [[COMMENT(0)]]
        and then pray for one another to be instantly healed,  for tremendous power
        is released through the passionate, heartfelt prayer  of a godly believer!
      comments:
      - number: 5:16
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic, which uses a word that can be
          translated \u201Cfaults\u201D or \u201Cfolly\u201D or \u201Coffenses.\u201D
          The Critical Greek text is \u201Cconfess your sins.\u201D      Or \u201Crestored.\u201D     
          Or \u201Cenergized prayer,\u201D a prayer within a prayer.    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Elijah was a man with human frailties, just like all of us, but he
        prayed and received supernatural answers. [[COMMENT(0)]] He actually shut
        the heavens over the land so there would be no rain for three and a half
        years! '
      comments:
      - number: 5:17
        content: "  Or \u201Che prayed with prayer\u201D (intensity).    "
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: Then he prayed again and the skies opened up over the land so that
        the rain came again and produced the harvest.
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Finally, as members of God\u2019s beloved family, we must go after
        the one who wanders from the truth and bring him back. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: For the one who restores the sinning believer back to God from the
        error of his way, gives back to his soul [[COMMENT(0)]] life from the dead,
        and covers over countless sins   by their demonstration of love!
      comments:
      - number: 5:20
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is similar, meaning
          \u201Csave his soul from death.\u201D      That is, bring about forgiveness
          of many sins through restoring the person back to God. To cover sins is
          a Hebrew concept of atonement.  "
